            <h1>Sitala Sasthi Celebration</h1>
            <p>A Divine Union of Shiva and Parvati</p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <div class="contain">
        <div class="main-content">
            <div class="card">
                <h2>Historical Significance</h2>
                <p>
                    Sitala Sasthi, celebrated for over 400 years, marks the divine marriage of Lord Shiva and Goddess Parvati.
                    Originating in Sambalpur, Odisha, it began when King Baliar Singh invited Utkal Brahmins from Puri to
                    perform the ritual. Symbolizing the end of summer’s heat with monsoon’s arrival, it’s a cherished
                    tradition reflecting Odisha’s spiritual and cultural depth.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <h2>Cultural Highlights</h2>
                <p>
                    The festival transforms Sambalpur into a carnival, with grand processions reenacting Shiva’s wedding
                    journey. Folk dances, Odissi music, and street performances by artists, including eunuchs, fill the air.
                    A chosen family acts as Parvati’s parents, offering her hand, blending mythology with vibrant community
                    participation.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <h2>Food and Cuisine</h2>
                <p>
                    Sitala Sasthi feasts feature Odia delicacies like Pakhala Bhata, Chhena Poda, and pithas (rice cakes).
                    Stalls offer jaggery sweets, spicy snacks, and cooling drinks like Bela Pana. The food celebrates the
                    season’s bounty, complementing the festive joy with rustic flavors.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <h2>Shopping Experience</h2>
                <p>
                    Markets bustle with stalls selling Sambalpuri textiles, handicrafts, and ritual items like betel nuts
                    and sacred threads. Visitors can buy souvenirs reflecting Odisha’s artistry, from woven fabrics to clay
                    idols. It’s a lively trade scene tied to the festival’s traditions.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <h2>Festive Atmosphere</h2>
                <p>
                    During Sitala Sasthi, Sambalpur becomes a living stage. The Sital Sasthi Yatra, a grand procession with
                    idols of Shiva and Parvati, winds through streets amid chants and music. The air buzzes with devotion
                    and celebration, uniting locals and visitors in a spectacular display of faith.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

